WHEREAS, Mr. Mann held a deep appreciation for Haywood County's history and was a
generous benefactor of its preservation; among his most cherished contributions was the
relocation and restoration of the one-room schoolhouse attended by the legendary Tina Turner,
an endeavor that transformed the structure into a curated tribute to her memory at Brownsville's
Welcome Center; and
WHEREAS, beyond his civic endeavors, Patrick Mann was a staunch advocate for the
arts, supporting the Jackson Symphony and serving as a board member of Lambuth College
and the Haywood County School Board; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Mann was an avid outdoorsman, and his love for the outdoors included
crafting birdhouses, feeding hummingbirds, hunting with his bird dogs, and having fishing
adventures across several continents. He embraced travel as a way of life, exploring national
parks, cities, and museums with his family; whether biking through Europe or hiking trails closer
to home, he and his wife shared an enduring love of discovery; and
WHEREAS, Patrick Mann was deeply devoted to his family and always endeavored to
remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, he will be sadly missed but fondly remembered by his beloved wife of sixty-
seven years, Ann Elizabeth Rule Mann; his children, Tanner (Lisa) Mann, John (Laura) Mann,
Elizabeth Mann, and David (Beth) Mann; his grandchildren, John-Michael (Kaitlynn) Mann,
Lauren (Ford) Ellington, Aiden (Jordyn) Riseling, Brenna Riseling, Logan Mann, Leah Mann,
Elizabeth Mann, and Kate Mann; four great-grandchildren; his brother, Bradford Dayton (Linda)
Mann, Sr.; and a host of cousins and friends; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Mann was preceded in death by his parents, Patrick Henry Mann, Sr.,
and Dorothy Mohon Mann; and
WHEREAS, Patrick Mann was wholly dedicated to his faith and an active member of
First United Methodist Church, which he served in numerous capacities; and
- 2 - 018052

WHEREAS, Mr. Mann leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in public
life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should pause to remember the bountiful life of this
exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Patrick Henry Mann, Jr.,
reflecting fondly upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the
examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Mann.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
